# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-filter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-filter/abarth] Carlo Abarth was sporting director of the Cisitalia racing team starting in 1947.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The following year, the manufacturer folded, and founder Piero Dusio flew to Argentina.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth, funded by Armando Scagliarini, took over Cisitalia's assets and on 31 March 1949, **Abarth & C.** was founded in Bologna.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Carlo's astrological sign, Scorpio, was chosen as the company logo.
[src:air-filter/abarth] From the Cisitalia liquidation, Abarth obtained five 204 sports cars (two complete Spiders and three unfinished), a D46 single-seater, and various spares.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The Cisitalia 204s were immediately rechristened Abarth Cisitalia 204A.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth proceeded to build and race a series of sports cars developed from these last Cisitalia cars.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In addition to Guido Scagliarini, the "Squadra Abarth" racing team lined up celebrated drivers, including Tazio Nuvolari, Franco Cortese, and Piero Taruffi.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Notably, Tazio Nuvolari made his last appearance in racing at the wheel of an Abarth 204A, winning its class in the Palermo–Monte Pellegrino hillclimb on 10 April 1950.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Alongside racing, the company's main activity was producing and selling accessories and performance parts for Fiat, Lancia, Cisitalia, and Simca cars, like inlet manifolds and silencers.
[src:air-filter/abarth] On 9 April 1951, the company's headquarters were moved to Turin; Abarth began his well-known association with Fiat in 1952, when the company built the Abarth 1500 Biposto on Fiat mechanicals.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In 1957, Abarth entered a deal with Fiat whereby they were paid direct fees for successful competition finishes.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth accordingly went on to enter their cars in countless hillclimbing and sports-car racing events across the world, mainly in classes from 850 to 2000 cc, competing with Porsche 904 and Ferrari Dino in the higher echelons.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Since they were paid based on the number of results, Abarth entered their cars in every conceivable class and in countries across the entire world.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Hans Herrmann was a factory driver from 1962 until 1965, winning the 500 km Nürburgring in 1963 with Teddy Pilette.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth promised Johann Abt that he could race a factory car for free if he won all the races he entered.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abt almost succeeded; of the 30 races he entered, Abt won 29 and finished second once.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth produced high-performance exhaust pipes, diversifying into tuning kits for road vehicles, mainly for Fiat.
[src:air-filter/abarth] A racing exhaust was produced for the 1950s Lambretta models "D" and "LD".
[src:air-filter/abarth] Original Abarth LD exhausts are now valuable collector's items.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Reproductions are available, which carry the Abarth name; how Fiat feels about this is not known.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Lambretta even held several 125 cc motorcycle land speed records during the 1950s due partly to the exhaust that Abarth developed for them.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In 1958, Abarth developed the Abarth Alfa Romeo 1000 in collaboration with the Milanese manufacturer.
[src:air-filter/abarth] They sent an engineer, Mario Colucci, to oversee the process.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth was impressed with his skill, and while the car remained a one-off, Colucci was given the position of Abarth's Technical Director in 1960.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Colucci's first design was a mid-engined, tubular framed roadster using the 750 engine called the **Abarth Spider Sport.** This car had an unfortunate gestation period and never attained much success in competition, while Abarth himself favored the rear-engine layout and kept offering both types.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The Spider Sport series was also built with 700 and 1000 cc displacements, while a few late examples were fitted with 1300 cc engines of Simca origins.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Colucci's next design, the Group 4 1000 SP, was much more successful and spawned a range of mid-engined, tubular-framed, fibreglass-bodied sports prototypes.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth also helped build sports or racing cars with Porsche and Simca.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Carlo sold Abarth to Fiat on 31 July 1971.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The acquisition was not made public until 15 October.
[src:air-filter/abarth] As Fiat was not interested in the Reparto Corse racing operations, these were taken over by Enzo Osella.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Osella obtained cars, spares, technicians, and drivers (amongst them Arturo Merzario), and continued the racing activity, founding the Osella racing team.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Thus ended for Abarth the days of sport prototype and hillclimb racing.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Under Fiat ownership, Abarth became the Fiat Group's racing department, managed by engine designer Aurelio Lampredi.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Abarth prepared Fiat's rally cars, including the Fiat 124 Abarth Rally and 131 Abarth.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In December 1977, in advance of the 1978 racing season, the beforehand competing Abarth and Squadra Corse Lancia factory racing operations were merged by Fiat into a single entity named EASA (*Ente per l'Attività Sportiva Automobilistica*, Organization for Car Sports Racing Activities).
[src:air-filter/abarth] Cesare Fiorio (previously in charge of the Lancia rally team) was appointed director, while Daniele Audetto was sporting director; the EASA headquarters were set up in Abarth's Corso Marche (Turin) offices.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The combined racing department developed the Lancia Beta Montecarlo Turbo Group 5 racing car which won the 1980 World Championship for Makes and the 1981 World Endurance Championship of Makes.
[src:air-filter/abarth] It also created the Lancia Rally 037 Group B rally car, which won for Lancia the 1983 World Manufacturers' Championship).
[src:air-filter/abarth] On 1 October 1981, Abarth & C. ceased to exist, and was replaced by Fiat Auto Gestione Sportiva, a division of the parent company specialised in the management of racing programmes that would remain in operation through to the end of 1999, when it changed to Fiat Auto Corse S.p.A.
[src:air-filter/abarth] Some commercial models built by Fiat or its subsidiaries Lancia and Autobianchi were co-branded Abarth, including the Autobianchi A112 Abarth, a lightweight and inexpensive "boy racer".
[src:air-filter/abarth] The A112 Abarth was introduced with a 58 hp engine, soon followed by a 70 hp one, and a specific "A112 Abarth trophy" was run from 1977 to 1984.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In the 1980s, Abarth name was mainly used to mark performance cars, such as the Fiat Ritmo Abarth 125/130 TC.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In 2000s, Fiat used the Abarth brand to designate a trim/model level, as in the Fiat Stilo Abarth.
[src:air-filter/abarth] On 1 February 2007, Abarth was re-established as an independent unit with the launch of the current company, Abarth & C.
[src:air-filter/abarth] S.p.A., controlled 100% by Fiat Group Automobiles S.p.A., the subsidiary of Fiat S.p.A. dealing with the production and selling of passenger cars and light commercial vehicles.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The first models launched were the Abarth Grande Punto and the Abarth Grande Punto S2000.
[src:air-filter/abarth] The brand is based in the Officine 83, part of the old Mirafiori engineering plant.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In 2015, Abarth's parent company was renamed FCA Italy S.p.A., reflecting the incorporation of Fiat S.p.A. into Fiat Chrysler Automobiles that took place in the previous months.
[src:air-filter/abarth] In 2017, Abarth collaborated with Yamaha to produce a limited-edition motorcycle, the "Sport Heritage café racer special".
[src:air-filter/abarth] Named the XSR900 Abarth it was based on the 847 cc inline-triple standard neo-retro Yamaha XSR900.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] An **absorption-compression heat pump** (**ACHP**) is a device that integrate an electric compressor in an absorption heat pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In some cases this is obtained by combining a vapor-compression heat pump and an absorption heat pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] It is also referred to as a hybrid heat pump which is however a broader field.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Thanks to this integration, the device can obtain cooling and heating effects using both thermal and electrical energy sources.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This type of systems is well coupled with cogeneration systems where both heat and electricity are produced.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Depending on the configuration, the system can maximize heating and cooling production from a given amount of fuel, or can improve the temperature (hence the quality) of waste heat from other processes.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This second use is the most studied one and has been applied to several industrial applications.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The first absorption-compression heat pump cycle concept was patented by Osenbrück.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Little research on it was done in the following years.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] in the 70s, the energy saving potential of the cycle grew in interest and there was a rapid increase in research activities in the field.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In this period several experimental plants were built and in 1997, Groll summarized this activities in its review where he identified more than 40 studies.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] At that time, considerable work was still needed before the ACHP could become commercially available.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Nordtvedt studied the cycle in his doctoral thesis and his studies ended up in the construction, in 2011, of the first commercial application in the Norwegian Food Industry.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] After this, several units have been installed for commercial use in various high temperature industrial applications.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantage with respect to compression heat pump is that the compression-absorption heat pumps allow the heat to be transfer with a temperature glide.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The compression heat pump uses a single pure working fluid, hence exchanges heat at a constant temperature.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption-compression heat pump uses instead a binary mixture where the condensation and evaporation occur with a temperature glide.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This property increases the efficiency of the heat transfer when the heat source also has a significant temperature glide, which is the typical condition found when dealing with waste heat recovery.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Being a hybrid solution that can exploit both heat and mechanical/electric energy sources, the device can be perfectly coupled with cogeneration units to produce heating and cooling at very high efficiencies.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Moreover, it makes the system more flexible, allowing the optimization of the mix of electricity and thermal energy.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Their availability vary in fact along the day and the year.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Therefore the flexibility allow to reduce the operating costs.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main drawback of this technology is that, to achieve good performances, they typically need to employ ammonia, which is very toxic and flammable.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This drawback resulted in the fact that these applications remained limited to the industrial sector, where it is more practical dealing with dangerous fluids.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most studied configuration is the so-called *compression heat pump with solution cycle* (CHPS) or *compression resorption heat pump* (CRHP), where the compressor is in parallel to the electric pump located between the absorber and the desorber.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration is used to increase the temperature of waste heat since it allow high absorption temperature at lower pressure than compression heat pumps.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Another possible configuration for the absorption compression heat pump is obtained from the combination of a gas-driven absorption heat pump (GAHP) with a vapor-compression heat pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration arises from the consideration that both cycles have in common a condenser, a lamination valve, and an evaporator.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main difference between the two is in the compression phase: where the compression heat pump uses an electric compressor, the gas-driven absorption heat pump uses a thermal compressor.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The ACHP is obtained by combining the components that are in common and using the electric and thermal compressor in parallel or in series.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Compression heat pumps use only a single fluid which is a refrigerant.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In contrast, absorption heat pump requires two fluids, a refrigerant and an absorbent able to absorb it.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] By combining the two devices, proper refrigerant absorbent pairs compatible with both the cycles are needed.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] There is a wide choice of refrigerants available for compression heat pumps.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption cycle is the one limiting the choice of the refrigerant.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most common refrigerants for absorption systems are ammonia and water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Both are good for combined absorption-compression heat pumps.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ammonia has an exceptionally good solubility in water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This is an important aspect that increases the performance and decreases the size of the device.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] However, its high toxicity and flammability reduces its attractiveness.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Water is a very attractive refrigerant because it is abundant, non-toxic, non-flammable and highly soluble in lithium bromide (LiBr).
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main issue with water is that, at the typical heat pump evaporator pressures, it freezes at 0 °C.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This makes water unsuitable for the applications where the cold sink goes below 0 °C, which is the typical winter operating condition of an air source heat pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorbent and refrigerant are strictly related to each other.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that ammonia is used as refrigerant, the most common absorbent is water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that water is used as refrigerant, as previously mentioned, the absorbent is usually LiBr.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ionic liquids have also been proposed as good absorbents, specially for water as refrigerant.
[src:air-filter/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantages of these salts is that they can be used under the conditions at which LiBr solution runs the risk of crystallization and they are less corrosive.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:air-filter/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Like surface tension, adsorption is a consequence of surface energy.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In a bulk material, all the bonding requirements (be they ionic, covalent, or metallic) of the constituent atoms of the material are fulfilled by other atoms in the material.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] However, atoms on the surface of the adsorbent are not wholly surrounded by other adsorbent atoms and therefore can attract adsorbates.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The exact nature of the bonding depends on the details of the species involved, but the adsorption process is generally classified as physisorption (characteristic of weak van der Waals forces) or chemisorption (characteristic of covalent bonding).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] It may also occur due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The nature of the adsorption can affect the structure of the adsorbed species.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] For example, polymer physisorption from solution can result in squashed structures on a surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Adsorption, ion exchange, and chromatography are sorption processes in which certain adsorbates are selectively transferred from the fluid phase to the surface of insoluble, rigid particles suspended in a vessel or packed in a column.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Pharmaceutical industry applications, which use adsorption as a means to prolong neurological exposure to specific drugs or parts thereof, are lesser known.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The word "adsorption" was coined in 1881 by German physicist Heinrich Kayser (1853–1940).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorption of gases and solutes is usually described through isotherms, that is, the amount of adsorbate on the adsorbent as a function of its pressure (if gas) or concentration (for liquid phase solutes) at constant temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The quantity adsorbed is nearly always normalized by the mass of the adsorbent to allow comparison of different materials.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] A number of different isotherm models have been developed.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] where x is the mass of adsorbate adsorbed, m is the mass of the adsorbent, P is the pressure of adsorbate (this can be changed to concentration if investigating solution rather than gas), and k and n are empirical constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The function is not adequate at very high pressure because in reality $x/m$ has an asymptotic maximum as pressure increases without bound.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As the temperature increases, the constants k and n change to reflect the empirical observation that the quantity adsorbed rises more slowly and higher pressures are required to saturate the surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Irving Langmuir was the first to derive a scientifically based adsorption isotherm in 1918.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The model applies to gases adsorbed on solid surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] It is a semi-empirical isotherm with a kinetic basis and was derived based on statistical thermodynamics.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] It is the most common isotherm equation to use due to its simplicity and its ability to fit a variety of adsorption data.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The surface is energetically homogeneous, and adsorbed molecules do not interact.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] At the maximum adsorption, only a monolayer is formed.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Adsorption only occurs on localized sites on the surface, not with other adsorbates.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] These four assumptions are seldom all true: there are always imperfections on the surface, adsorbed molecules are not necessarily inert, and the mechanism is clearly not the same for the first molecules to adsorb to a surface as for the last.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The fourth condition is the most troublesome, as frequently more molecules will adsorb to the monolayer; this problem is addressed by the BET isotherm for relatively flat (non-microporous) surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is nonetheless the first choice for most models of adsorption and has many applications in surface kinetics (usually called Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics) and thermodynamics.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Langmuir suggested that adsorption takes place through this mechanism: $A_{\text{g}}+S\rightleftharpoons AS$ , where *A* is a gas molecule, and *S* is an adsorption site.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The direct and inverse rate constants are *k* and *k*−1.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] where P is the partial pressure of the gas or the molar concentration of the solution.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] For very low pressures $\theta \approx KP$ , and for high pressures $\theta \approx 1$ .
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The value of $\theta$ is difficult to measure experimentally; usually, the adsorbate is a gas and the quantity adsorbed is given in moles, grams, or gas volumes at standard temperature and pressure (STP) per gram of adsorbent.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Through its slope and *y* intercept we can obtain *v*mon and *K*, which are constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] *v*mon is related to the number of adsorption sites through the ideal gas law.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] If we assume that the number of sites is just the whole area of the solid divided into the cross section of the adsorbate molecules, we can easily calculate the surface area of the adsorbent.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The surface area of an adsorbent depends on its structure: the more pores it has, the greater the area, which has a big influence on reactions on surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] where *i* is each one of the gases that adsorb.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] 1) To choose between the Langmuir and Freundlich equations, the enthalpies of adsorption must be investigated.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] While the Langmuir model assumes that the energy of adsorption remains constant with surface occupancy, the Freundlich equation is derived with the assumption that the heat of adsorption continually decrease as the binding sites are occupied.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The choice of the model based on best fitting of the data is a common misconception.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] 2) The use of the linearized form of the Langmuir model is no longer common practice.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Advances in computational power allowed for nonlinear regression to be performed quickly and with higher confidence since no data transformation is required.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Often molecules do form multilayers, that is, some are adsorbed on already adsorbed molecules, and the Langmuir isotherm is not valid.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In 1938 Stephen Brunauer, Paul Emmett, and Edward Teller developed a model isotherm that takes that possibility into account.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Their theory is called BET theory, after the initials in their last names.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The derivation of the formula is more complicated than Langmuir's (see links for complete derivation).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The key assumption used in deriving the BET equation that the successive heats of adsorption for all layers except the first are equal to the heat of condensation of the adsorbate.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is usually better for chemisorption, and the BET isotherm works better for physisorption for non-microporous surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In other instances, molecular interactions between gas molecules previously adsorbed on a solid surface form significant interactions with gas molecules in the gaseous phases.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Hence, adsorption of gas molecules to the surface is more likely to occur around gas molecules that are already present on the solid surface, rendering the Langmuir adsorption isotherm ineffective for the purposes of modelling.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This effect was studied in a system where nitrogen was the adsorbate and tungsten was the adsorbent by Paul Kisliuk (1922–2008) in 1957.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] To compensate for the increased probability of adsorption occurring around molecules present on the substrate surface, Kisliuk developed the precursor state theory, whereby molecules would enter a precursor state at the interface between the solid adsorbent and adsorbate in the gaseous phase.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] From here, adsorbate molecules would either adsorb to the adsorbent or desorb into the gaseous phase.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The probability of adsorption occurring from the precursor state is dependent on the adsorbate's proximity to other adsorbate molecules that have already been adsorbed.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] If an adsorbate molecule enters the precursor state at a location that is remote from any other previously adsorbed adsorbate molecules, the sticking probability is reflected by the size of the SD constant.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As SD is dictated by factors that are taken into account by the Langmuir model, SD can be assumed to be the adsorption rate constant.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] However, the rate constant for the Kisliuk model (*R*') is different from that of the Langmuir model, as *R*' is used to represent the impact of diffusion on monolayer formation and is proportional to the square root of the system's diffusion coefficient.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As can be seen in the formula, the variation of *K* must be isosteric, that is, at constant coverage.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] that is to say, adsorption is more exothermic than liquefaction.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorption of ensemble molecules on a surface or interface can be divided into two processes: adsorption and desorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] If the adsorption rate wins the desorption rate, the molecules will accumulate over time giving the adsorption curve over time.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] If the desorption rate is larger, the number of molecules on the surface will decrease over time.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorption rate is dependent on the temperature, the diffusion rate of the solute (related to mean free path for pure gas), and the energy barrier between the molecule and the surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The diffusion and key elements of the adsorption rate can be calculated using Fick's laws of diffusion and the Einstein relation (kinetic theory).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] where A is the surface area (unit m2), C is the number concentration of the molecule in the bulk solution (unit #/m3), D is the diffusion constant (unit m2/s), and t is time (unit s).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Further simulations and analysis of this equation show that the square root dependence on the time is originated from the decrease of the concentrations near the surface under ideal adsorption conditions.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Also, this equation only works for the beginning of the adsorption when a well-behaved concentration gradient forms near the surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Correction on the reduction of the adsorption area and slowing down of the concentration gradient evolution have to be considered over a longer time.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Under real experimental conditions, the flow and the small adsorption area always make the adsorption rate faster than what this equation predicted, and the energy barrier will either accelerate this rate by surface attraction or slow it down by surface repulsion.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Thus, the prediction from this equation is often a few to several orders of magnitude away from the experimental results.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The desorption of a molecule from the surface depends on the binding energy of the molecule to the surface and the temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The typical overall adsorption rate is thus often a combined result of the adsorption and desorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Since 1980 two theories were worked on to explain adsorption and obtain equations that work.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] These two are referred to as the chi hypothesis, the quantum mechanical derivation, and excess surface work (ESW).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] where "ads" stands for "adsorbed", "m" stands for "monolayer equivalence" and "vap" is reference to the vapor pressure of the liquid adsorptive at the same temperature as the solid sample.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The plot of $n_{ads}$ adsorbed versus $\chi$ is referred to as the chi plot.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] For flat surfaces, the slope of the chi plot yields the surface area.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Empirically, this plot was noticed as being a very good fit to the isotherm by Michael Polanyi and also by Jan Hendrik de Boer and Cornelis Zwikker but not pursued.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This was due to criticism in the former case by Albert Einstein and in the latter case by Brunauer.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This flat surface equation may be used as a "standard curve" in the normal tradition of comparison curves, with the exception that the porous sample's early portion of the plot of $n_{ads}$ versus $\chi$ acts as a self-standard.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Ultramicroporous, microporous, and mesoporous conditions may be analyzed using this technique.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Typical standard deviations for full isotherm fits including porous samples are less than 2%.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Notice that in this description of physical adsorption, the entropy of adsorption is consistent with the Dubinin thermodynamic criterion, that is the entropy of adsorption from the liquid state to the adsorbed state is approximately zero.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Adsorbents are used usually in the form of spherical pellets, rods, moldings, or monoliths with a hydrodynamic radius between 0.25 and 5 millimetres (0.0098 and 0.1969 in).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] They must have high abrasion resistance, high thermal stability, and small pore diameters, which results in higher exposed surface area and hence high capacity for adsorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorbents must also have a distinct pore structure that enables fast transport of the gaseous vapors.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Silica gel is a chemically inert, non-toxic, polar, and dimensionally stable (< 400 °C or 750 °F) amorphous form of SiO2.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] It is prepared by the reaction between sodium silicate and acetic acid, which is followed by a series of after-treatment processes such as aging, pickling, etc.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] These after-treatment methods results in various pore size distributions.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Silica is used for drying of process air (e.g. oxygen, natural gas) and adsorption of heavy (polar) hydrocarbons from natural gas.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Zeolites are natural or synthetic crystalline aluminosilicates, which have a repeating pore network and release water at high temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] They are manufactured by hydrothermal synthesis of sodium aluminosilicate or another silica source in an autoclave followed by ion exchange with certain cations (Na+, Li+, Ca2+, K+, NH4+).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The channel diameter of zeolite cages usually ranges from 2 to 9 Å.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The ion exchange process is followed by drying of the crystals, which can be pelletized with a binder to form macroporous pellets.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Zeolites are applied in drying of process air, CO2 removal from natural gas, CO removal from reforming gas, air separation, catalytic cracking, and catalytic synthesis and reforming.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Non-polar (siliceous) zeolites are synthesized from aluminum-free silica sources or by dealumination of aluminum-containing zeolites.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The dealumination process is done by treating the zeolite with steam at elevated temperatures, typically greater than 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This high-temperature heat treatment breaks the aluminum-oxygen bonds and the aluminum atom is expelled from the zeolite framework.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The term "adsorption" itself was coined by Heinrich Kayser in 1881 in the context of uptake of gases by carbons.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Activated carbon is a highly porous, amorphous solid consisting of microcrystallites with a graphite lattice, usually prepared in small pellets or a powder.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] One of its main drawbacks is that it reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures (over 300 °C (572 °F)).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Activated carbon can be manufactured from carbonaceous material, including coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite), peat, wood, or nutshells (e.g., coconut).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The manufacturing process consists of two phases: carbonization and activation.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The carbonization process includes drying and then heating to separate by-products, including tars and other hydrocarbons from the raw material, as well as to drive off any gases generated.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The process is completed by heating the material over 400 °C (750 °F) in an oxygen-free atmosphere that cannot support combustion.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The carbonized particles are then "activated" by exposing them to an oxidizing agent, usually steam or carbon dioxide, at high temperature.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This agent burns off the pore-blocking structures created during the carbonization phase, and so they develop a porous, three-dimensional graphite lattice structure.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The size of the pores developed during activation is a function of the time that they spend in this stage.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Longer exposure times result in larger pore sizes.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The most popular aqueous phase carbons are bituminous based because of their hardness, abrasion resistance, pore size distribution, and low cost, but their effectiveness needs to be tested in each application to determine the optimal product.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Activated carbon is used for adsorption of organic substances and non-polar adsorbates and it is also usually used for waste gas (and waste water) treatment.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] It is the most widely used adsorbent since most of its chemical (e.g. surface groups) and physical properties (e.g. pore size distribution and surface area) can be tuned according to what is needed.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Its usefulness also derives from its large micropore (and sometimes mesopore) volume and the resulting high surface area.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Recent research works reported activated carbon as an effective agent to adsorb cationic species of toxic metals from multi-pollutant systems and also proposed possible adsorption mechanisms with supporting evidences.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorption of water at surfaces is of broad importance in chemical engineering, materials science, and catalysis.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Also termed surface hydration, the presence of physically or chemically adsorbed water at the surfaces of solids plays an important role in governing interface properties, chemical reaction pathways, and catalytic performance in a wide range of systems.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In the case of physically adsorbed water, surface hydration can be eliminated simply through drying at conditions of temperature and pressure allowing full vaporization of water.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The low cost ($200/ton) and high cycle rate (2,000 ×) of synthetic zeolites such as Linde 13X with water adsorbate has garnered much academic and commercial interest recently for use for thermal energy storage (TES), specifically of low-grade solar and waste heat.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Several pilot projects have been funded in the EU from 2000 to the present (2020).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The basic concept is to store solar thermal energy as chemical latent energy in the zeolite.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Typically, hot dry air from flat plate solar collectors is made to flow through a bed of zeolite such that any water adsorbate present is driven off.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Storage can be diurnal, weekly, monthly, or even seasonal depending on the volume of the zeolite and the area of the solar thermal panels.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] When heat is called for during the night, or sunless hours, or winter, humidified air flows through the zeolite.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As the humidity is adsorbed by the zeolite, heat is released to the air and subsequently to the building space.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This form of TES, with specific use of zeolites, was first taught by John Guerra in 1978.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Typical adsorbents proposed for carbon capture and storage are zeolites and MOFs.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The customization of adsorbents makes them a potentially attractive alternative to absorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Because adsorbents can be regenerated by temperature or pressure swing, this step can be less energy intensive than absorption regeneration methods.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Major problems that are present with adsorption cost in carbon capture are: regenerating the adsorbent, mass ratio, solvent/MOF, cost of adsorbent, production of the adsorbent, lifetime of adsorbent.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In sorption enhanced water gas shift (SEWGS) technology a pre-combustion carbon capture process, based on solid adsorption, is combined with the water-gas shift reaction (WGS) in order to produce a high pressure hydrogen stream.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The CO2 stream produced can be stored or used for other industrial processes.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Protein adsorption is a process that has a fundamental role in the field of biomaterials.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Indeed, biomaterial surfaces in contact with biological media, such as blood or serum, are immediately coated by proteins.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Therefore, living cells do not interact directly with the biomaterial surface, but with the adsorbed proteins layer.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This protein layer mediates the interaction between biomaterials and cells, translating biomaterial physical and chemical properties into a "biological language".
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In fact, cell membrane receptors bind to protein layer bioactive sites and these receptor-protein binding events are transduced, through the cell membrane, in a manner that stimulates specific intracellular processes that then determine cell adhesion, shape, growth, and differentiation.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Protein adsorption is influenced by many surface properties such as surface wettability, surface chemical composition, and surface nanometre-scale morphology.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Surfactant adsorption is a similar phenomenon, but utilising surfactant molecules in the place of proteins.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Combining an adsorbent with a refrigerant, adsorption chillers use heat to provide a cooling effect.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This heat, in the form of hot water, may come from any number of industrial sources including waste heat from industrial processes, prime heat from solar thermal installations or from the exhaust or water jacket heat of a piston engine or turbine.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Although there are similarities between adsorption chillers and absorption refrigeration, the former is based on the interaction between gases and solids.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The adsorption chamber of the chiller is filled with a solid material (for example zeolite, silica gel, alumina, active carbon or certain types of metal salts), which in its neutral state has adsorbed the refrigerant.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] When heated, the solid desorbs (releases) refrigerant vapour, which subsequently is cooled and liquefied.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This liquid refrigerant then provides a cooling effect at the evaporator from its enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In the final stage the refrigerant vapour is (re)adsorbed into the solid.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As an adsorption chiller requires no compressor, it is relatively quiet.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Portal site mediated adsorption is a model for site-selective activated gas adsorption in metallic catalytic systems that contain a variety of different adsorption sites.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In such systems, low-coordination "edge and corner" defect-like sites can exhibit significantly lower adsorption enthalpies than high-coordination (basal plane) sites.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] As a result, these sites can serve as "portals" for very rapid adsorption to the rest of the surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The phenomenon relies on the common "spillover" effect (described below), where certain adsorbed species exhibit high mobility on some surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The model explains seemingly inconsistent observations of gas adsorption thermodynamics and kinetics in catalytic systems where surfaces can exist in a range of coordination structures, and it has been successfully applied to bimetallic catalytic systems where synergistic activity is observed.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In contrast to pure spillover, portal site adsorption refers to surface diffusion to adjacent adsorption sites, not to non-adsorptive support surfaces.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The model appears to have been first proposed for carbon monoxide on silica-supported platinum by Brandt *et al.* (1993).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] A similar, but independent model was developed by King and co-workers to describe hydrogen adsorption on silica-supported alkali promoted ruthenium, silver-ruthenium, and copper-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The same group applied the model to CO hydrogenation (Fischer–Tropsch synthesis).
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Zupanc *et al.* (2002) subsequently confirmed the same model for hydrogen adsorption on magnesia-supported caesium-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Trens *et al.* (2009) have similarly described CO surface diffusion on carbon-supported Pt particles of varying morphology.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The presence of the metal serves as a lower-energy pathway for gaseous species to first adsorb to the metal and then diffuse on the support surface.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] This is possible because the adsorbed species attains a lower energy state once it has adsorbed to the metal, thus lowering the activation barrier between the gas phase species and the support-adsorbed species.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Hydrogen spillover is the most common example of an adsorptive spillover.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] In the case of hydrogen, adsorption is most often accompanied with dissociation of molecular hydrogen (H2) to atomic hydrogen (H), followed by spillover of the hydrogen atoms present.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The spillover effect has been used to explain many observations in heterogeneous catalysis and adsorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Adsorption of molecules onto polymer surfaces is central to a number of applications, including development of non-stick coatings and in various biomedical devices.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Polymers may also be adsorbed to surfaces through polyelectrolyte adsorption.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Adsorption is the beginning of viral entry, which is the earliest stage of infection in the viral life cycle.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The next steps are penetration, uncoating, synthesis (transcription if needed, and translation), and release.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The virus replication cycle, in this respect, is similar for all types of viruses.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Factors such as transcription may or may not be needed if the virus is able to integrate its genomic information in the cell's nucleus, or if the virus can replicate itself directly within the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] The game of *Tetris* is a puzzle game in which blocks of 4 are adsorbed onto a surface during game play.
[src:air-filter/adsorption] Scientists have used *Tetris* blocks "as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape" and their "adsorption on a flat surface" for studying the thermodynamics of nanoparticles.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:air-filter/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:air-filter/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:air-filter/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:air-filter/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:air-filter/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:air-filter/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:air-filter/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:air-filter/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
